        args='{"final_result": "## Capex-to-Revenue Ratio Comparison: AWS vs. SpaceX AI Segment\\n\\n### 1. Verified Figures from SEC Filings\\n\\n**Amazon (FY2025 10-K, filed February 6, 2026):**\\n| Metric | Value |\\n|---|---|\\n| AWS Net Sales (Revenue) | $128,725 million |\\n| Consolidated Purchases of Property & Equipment (Cash Flow Statement) | $131,819 million |\\n| AWS-Specific Net Additions to Property & Equipment | $96,496 million |\\n| AWS Segment Operating Income | $45,606 million |\\n\\n**SpaceX (S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — recast consolidated entity including xAI and X Holdings):**\\n| Metric | Value |\\n|---|---|\\n| AI Segment Revenue (FY2025) | $3,201 million |\\n| AI Segment Capex (FY2025 full year) | $12,727 million |\\n| AI Segment Capex (Q1 2026, three months ended March 31) | $7,723 million |\\n| AI Segment Loss from Operations (FY2025) | $(6,355) million |\\n| AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA (FY2025) | $(1,237) million |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. Capex-to-Revenue Calculations\\n\\n**AWS (using consolidated Amazon capex as proxy, per the question\'s instruction):**\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{\\\\$131{,}819\\\\text{M}}{\\\\$128{,}725\\\\text{M}} = 1.02\\\\text{x} \\\\quad (102.4\\\\%)$$\\n\\n*For reference, using AWS-specific capex only:*\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{\\\\$96{,}496\\\\text{M}}{\\\\$128{,}725\\\\text{M}} = 0.75\\\\text{x} \\\\quad (75.0\\\\%)$$\\n\\n**SpaceX AI Segment (annualized Q1 2026 capex):**\\n\\nAnnualized Q1 2026 capex = $7,723M × 4 = **$30,892 million**\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{\\\\$30{,}892\\\\text{M}}{\\\\$3{,}201\\\\text{M}} = 9.65\\\\text{x} \\\\quad (965\\\\%)$$\\n\\n*For reference, using FY2025 actual full-year AI capex:*\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{\\\\$12{,}727\\\\text{M}}{\\\\$3{,}201\\\\text{M}} = 3.98\\\\text{x} \\\\quad (398\\\\%)$$\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. Summary Table\\n\\n| Metric | AWS (Consolidated Proxy) | SpaceX AI (Annualized Q1 \'26) | SpaceX AI (FY2025 Actual) |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| Revenue | $128.7B | $3.2B | $3.2B |\\n| Capex | $131.8B | $30.9B (annualized) | $12.7B |\\n| **Capex / Revenue** | **1.02x** | **9.65x** | **3.98x** |\\n| Operating Income/(Loss) | $45.6B (35.4% margin) | N/A (FY: $(6.4B) loss) | $(6.4B) loss |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. What the Comparison Implies About Infrastructure Buildout vs. Monetization Maturity\\n\\nThe ~9.5x gap between the two ratios (9.65x vs. 1.02x) is analytically stark and reflects fundamentally different positions on the infrastructure-investment lifecycle:\\n\\n**AWS — Mature Monetization Phase:**\\nAWS\'s capex-to-revenue ratio of ~1.02x (consolidated) or ~0.75x (AWS-specific) indicates that its infrastructure spending is approximately covered by current-period revenue. AWS generated $45.6 billion in operating income on $128.7 billion in revenue (a 35.4% operating margin), demonstrating that its infrastructure buildout has already achieved scale-efficient monetization. AWS is investing for growth and AI capacity expansion, but from a position of proven, profitable unit economics. Its $244 billion in remaining performance obligations (backlog) further confirms deep revenue visibility against which capex is being deployed.\\n\\n**SpaceX AI Segment — Pre-Revenue-Scale Infrastructure Buildout:**\\nThe AI segment\'s annualized capex-to-revenue ratio of 9.65x means it is spending nearly **$10 on infrastructure for every $1 of revenue** it generates. Even using FY2025 actual capex, the ratio was 3.98x. The S-1 explicitly describes the segment as being in an \\"earlier stage of development\\" operating in a \\"nascent and rapidly evolving market\\" with a \\"multi-year investment horizon\\" before achieving sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. The segment reported a $(6,355) million operating loss and $(1,237) million Adjusted EBITDA in FY2025. The Q1 2026 capex acceleration (from $2,567M in Q1 2025 to $7,723M in Q1 2026, a 3x increase) signals that the buildout is intensifying well ahead of revenue scaling.\\n\\n**Implication:** AWS is in a *harvest-and-expand* phase where capex is funded by and proportionate to an established revenue base. SpaceX\'s AI segment is in a *build-then-monetize* phase where capex is massively front-loaded relative to current revenue, with monetization expected to follow infrastructure deployment by multiple years.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. Structural Difference in Compute-Business Models: Why a Direct Multiple Comparison Is Analytically Incomplete\\n\\nA direct capex-to-revenue multiple comparison between AWS and SpaceX\'s AI segment is analytically incomplete because of a fundamental structural difference in how each entity\'s compute business operates:\\n\\n**AWS operates a public cloud utility model (infrastructure-as-a-service):**\\n- Revenue is generated by selling generalized, on-demand compute, storage, and services to millions of diverse customers on a metered (usage-based) or committed-term basis.\\n- Infrastructure is a shared, multi-tenant platform where capex is directly and continuously converted into billable service capacity.\\n- The capex-to-revenue ratio reflects a relatively tight feedback loop: deploy servers → customers consume → revenue flows.\\n- Revenue scales roughly proportionally with infrastructure deployment.\\n\\n**SpaceX\'s AI segment operates a captive-first, vertically integrated AGI-development model:**\\n- Infrastructure is built **primarily to train proprietary frontier models** (Grok) and power the X platform — not to serve as a general-purpose public cloud.\\n- Third-party monetization is **secondary and selective**: the S-1 discloses that compute is sold to a \\"limited number of third-party customers\\" (e.g., the $1.25B/month Anthropic agreement, the $8.5B Cursor deferred services arrangement) to ensure capacity remains available for internal AGI development.\\n- Revenue streams are heterogeneous and not purely compute-consumption-based: they include advertising on X, consumer/enterprise subscriptions (X Premium, Grok), data licensing, and API access — many of which are not directly proportional to capex deployed.\\n- The segment\'s infrastructure economics are optimized for **\\"cost per token\\"** of AI training and inference, not for maximizing third-party revenue per dollar of capex.\\n\\n**Why this makes direct comparison incomplete:**\\n1. **Revenue is not the correct denominator for SpaceX\'s AI capex.** A significant portion of SpaceX\'s AI infrastructure spending generates value through proprietary model capabilities (Grok), platform enhancement (X), and strategic positioning — value that does not flow through the revenue line in the way AWS\'s infrastructure spend does.\\n2. **AWS\'s consolidated capex includes non-AWS spending** (~$35.9B for North America, ~$7.6B International, ~$2.3B Corporate), making the consolidated proxy an overstatement of AWS-specific infrastructure intensity.\\n3. **Timing mismatch:** SpaceX\'s Q1 2026 capex reflects an acceleration phase (COLOSSUS II deployment in 91 days), while AWS\'s FY2025 capex reflects steady-state expansion of a 20-year-old platform.\\n4. **Revenue composition differs fundamentally:** AWS revenue is almost entirely infrastructure-consumption-driven; SpaceX AI revenue includes advertising, subscriptions, and licensing that are not direct functions of compute capacity deployed.\\n\\nA more analytically complete comparison would require normalizing for: (a) the proportion of capex dedicated to revenue-generating vs. internal-R&D infrastructure, (b) the expected monetization timeline and terminal revenue capacity of deployed infrastructure, and (c) the non-revenue strategic value of proprietary model development embedded in SpaceX\'s capex.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Sources\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1018724/000101872426000004/amzn-20251231.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Amazon.com, Inc. FY2025 10-K (filed February 6, 2026)\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Capex-to-Revenue Ratio Comparison: AWS vs. SpaceX AI Segment\n\n### 1. Verified Figures from SEC Filings\n\n**Amazon (FY2025 10-K, filed February 6, 2026):**\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| AWS Net Sales (Revenue) | $128,725 million |\n| Consolidated Purchases of Property & Equipment (Cash Flow Statement) | $131,819 million |\n| AWS-Specific Net Additions to Property & Equipment | $96,496 million |\n| AWS Segment Operating Income | $45,606 million |\n\n**SpaceX (S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — recast consolidated entity including xAI and X Holdings):**\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| AI Segment Revenue (FY2025) | $3,201 million |\n| AI Segment Capex (FY2025 full year) | $12,727 million |\n| AI Segment Capex (Q1 2026, three months ended March 31) | $7,723 million |\n| AI Segment Loss from Operations (FY2025) | $(6,355) million |\n| AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA (FY2025) | $(1,237) million |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Capex-to-Revenue Calculations\n\n**AWS (using consolidated Amazon capex as proxy, per the question\'s instruction):**\n\n$$\\frac{\\$131{,}819\\text{M}}{\\$128{,}725\\text{M}} = 1.02\\text{x} \\quad (102.4\\%)$$\n\n*For reference, using AWS-specific capex only:*\n\n$$\\frac{\\$96{,}496\\text{M}}{\\$128{,}725\\text{M}} = 0.75\\text{x} \\quad (75.0\\%)$$\n\n**SpaceX AI Segment (annualized Q1 2026 capex):**\n\nAnnualized Q1 2026 capex = $7,723M × 4 = **$30,892 million**\n\n$$\\frac{\\$30{,}892\\text{M}}{\\$3{,}201\\text{M}} = 9.65\\text{x} \\quad (965\\%)$$\n\n*For reference, using FY2025 actual full-year AI capex:*\n\n$$\\frac{\\$12{,}727\\text{M}}{\\$3{,}201\\text{M}} = 3.98\\text{x} \\quad (398\\%)$$\n\n---\n\n### 3. Summary Table\n\n| Metric | AWS (Consolidated Proxy) | SpaceX AI (Annualized Q1 \'26) | SpaceX AI (FY2025 Actual) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | $128.7B | $3.2B | $3.2B |\n| Capex | $131.8B | $30.9B (annualized) | $12.7B |\n| **Capex / Revenue** | **1.02x** | **9.65x** | **3.98x** |\n| Operating Income/(Loss) | $45.6B (35.4% margin) | N/A (FY: $(6.4B) loss) | $(6.4B) loss |\n\n---\n\n### 4. What the Comparison Implies About Infrastructure Buildout vs. Monetization Maturity\n\nThe ~9.5x gap between the two ratios (9.65x vs. 1.02x) is analytically stark and reflects fundamentally different positions on the infrastructure-investment lifecycle:\n\n**AWS — Mature Monetization Phase:**\nAWS\'s capex-to-revenue ratio of ~1.02x (consolidated) or ~0.75x (AWS-specific) indicates that its infrastructure spending is approximately covered by current-period revenue. AWS generated $45.6 billion in operating income on $128.7 billion in revenue (a 35.4% operating margin), demonstrating that its infrastructure buildout has already achieved scale-efficient monetization. AWS is investing for growth and AI capacity expansion, but from a position of proven, profitable unit economics. Its $244 billion in remaining performance obligations (backlog) further confirms deep revenue visibility against which capex is being deployed.\n\n**SpaceX AI Segment — Pre-Revenue-Scale Infrastructure Buildout:**\nThe AI segment\'s annualized capex-to-revenue ratio of 9.65x means it is spending nearly **$10 on infrastructure for every $1 of revenue** it generates. Even using FY2025 actual capex, the ratio was 3.98x. The S-1 explicitly describes the segment as being in an "earlier stage of development" operating in a "nascent and rapidly evolving market" with a "multi-year investment horizon" before achieving sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA. The segment reported a $(6,355) million operating loss and $(1,237) million Adjusted EBITDA in FY2025. The Q1 2026 capex acceleration (from $2,567M in Q1 2025 to $7,723M in Q1 2026, a 3x increase) signals that the buildout is intensifying well ahead of revenue scaling.\n\n**Implication:** AWS is in a *harvest-and-expand* phase where capex is funded by and proportionate to an established revenue base. SpaceX\'s AI segment is in a *build-then-monetize* phase where capex is massively front-loaded relative to current revenue, with monetization expected to follow infrastructure deployment by multiple years.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Structural Difference in Compute-Business Models: Why a Direct Multiple Comparison Is Analytically Incomplete\n\nA direct capex-to-revenue multiple comparison between AWS and SpaceX\'s AI segment is analytically incomplete because of a fundamental structural difference in how each entity\'s compute business operates:\n\n**AWS operates a public cloud utility model (infrastructure-as-a-service):**\n- Revenue is generated by selling generalized, on-demand compute, storage, and services to millions of diverse customers on a metered (usage-based) or committed-term basis.\n- Infrastructure is a shared, multi-tenant platform where capex is directly and continuously converted into billable service capacity.\n- The capex-to-revenue ratio reflects a relatively tight feedback loop: deploy servers → customers consume → revenue flows.\n- Revenue scales roughly proportionally with infrastructure deployment.\n\n**SpaceX\'s AI segment operates a captive-first, vertically integrated AGI-development model:**\n- Infrastructure is built **primarily to train proprietary frontier models** (Grok) and power the X platform — not to serve as a general-purpose public cloud.\n- Third-party monetization is **secondary and selective**: the S-1 discloses that compute is sold to a "limited number of third-party customers" (e.g., the $1.25B/month Anthropic agreement, the $8.5B Cursor deferred services arrangement) to ensure capacity remains available for internal AGI development.\n- Revenue streams are heterogeneous and not purely compute-consumption-based: they include advertising on X, consumer/enterprise subscriptions (X Premium, Grok), data licensing, and API access — many of which are not directly proportional to capex deployed.\n- The segment\'s infrastructure economics are optimized for **"cost per token"** of AI training and inference, not for maximizing third-party revenue per dollar of capex.\n\n**Why this makes direct comparison incomplete:**\n1. **Revenue is not the correct denominator for SpaceX\'s AI capex.** A significant portion of SpaceX\'s AI infrastructure spending generates value through proprietary model capabilities (Grok), platform enhancement (X), and strategic positioning — value that does not flow through the revenue line in the way AWS\'s infrastructure spend does.\n2. **AWS\'s consolidated capex includes non-AWS spending** (~$35.9B for North America, ~$7.6B International, ~$2.3B Corporate), making the consolidated proxy an overstatement of AWS-specific infrastructure intensity.\n3. **Timing mismatch:** SpaceX\'s Q1 2026 capex reflects an acceleration phase (COLOSSUS II deployment in 91 days), while AWS\'s FY2025 capex reflects steady-state expansion of a 20-year-old platform.\n4. **Revenue composition differs fundamentally:** AWS revenue is almost entirely infrastructure-consumption-driven; SpaceX AI revenue includes advertising, subscriptions, and licensing that are not direct functions of compute capacity deployed.\n\nA more analytically complete comparison would require normalizing for: (a) the proportion of capex dedicated to revenue-generating vs. internal-R&D infrastructure, (b) the expected monetization timeline and terminal revenue capacity of deployed infrastructure, and (c) the non-revenue strategic value of proprietary model development embedded in SpaceX\'s capex.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n```json\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1018724/000101872426000004/amzn-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Amazon.com, Inc. FY2025 10-K (filed February 6, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```'
